\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 IT Asset Catalog
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations shall maintain a current IT Asset Catalog in the designated system of record (Redmine).
 The catalog shall enumerate all hardware models,
 software titles,
 and services that fall within the operational purview of the Information Operations Department,
 regardless of asset support tier as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.

\series default
 The IT Asset Catalog is an internal operational reference document maintained for IT Department use and shall not be published to general County staff.
 The IT Director holds sole authority to establish and approve the catalog and its contents.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure the catalog is maintained current in Redmine and shall present the catalog for IT Director review and approval no less than annually and following any significant change to the County's technology environment,
 contract portfolio,
 or vendor relationships.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Asset Lifecycle Status Classifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Every hardware model,
 software title,
 and service enumerated in the IT Asset Catalog shall carry one of the following three lifecycle status classifications.
 These classifications govern the IT Department's support commitment for each item and inform service level obligations as defined in Section 6.4 of this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Supported
\series default
 status designates hardware,
 software,
 or services that are fully endorsed and actively supported by the Information Operations Department.
 Assets carrying Supported status represent the standard authorized technology environment for Elko County.
 The IT Department shall fulfill its full service level commitments for Supported assets as defined in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Deprecated
\series default
 status designates hardware,
 software,
 or services that remain operational but have been formally identified for replacement.
 At the time of Deprecated classification,
 the IT Director shall establish and document a mandatory replacement deadline in the IT Asset Catalog.
 Deprecated assets are no longer authorized for new deployments or expanded use.
 The IT Department shall provide best-effort support for Deprecated assets within the labor ceiling defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 for the duration of the replacement window.
 Upon reaching the replacement deadline,
 the asset shall automatically transition to Unsupported status unless the IT Director has formally authorized an extension in writing,
 documented in the IT Asset Catalog with a new deadline and supporting rationale.
 No open-ended extensions shall be granted.
 The IT Director may,
 by written notation in the work order,
 authorize continued remediation beyond the standard labor ceiling.
 Such authorization constitutes a deliberate project-level commitment and supersedes the Deprecated asset replacement preference for the duration of the authorized effort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unsupported
\series default
 status designates hardware,
 software,
 or services that the Information Operations Department does not support and will not remediate.
 Unsupported assets represent an active operational and security risk and shall be prioritized for immediate replacement or decommissioning under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Work orders submitted for Unsupported assets shall be closed with a documented replacement referral.
 The IT Department's obligation for Unsupported assets is limited to documenting the referral and initiating the replacement process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall approve all lifecycle status classifications and reclassifications.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that classification reviews are conducted no less than annually and whenever a vendor announces end-of-life,
 a contract expires,
 a security risk materially changes,
 or a replacement technology is formally adopted.
 Reclassification proposals shall be prepared by the Assistant IT Director,
 documented with the proposed effective date and supporting rationale,
 and submitted to the IT Director for approval prior to implementation in the IT Asset Catalog.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Triage and Severity Classification Authority
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All work orders submitted to the Information Operations Department shall undergo IT-side triage prior to the commencement of active work.
 User-submitted severity levels represent the requester's assessment and shall be treated as an input to triage,
 not as a binding operational classification.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall confirm or reclassify the severity level based on verified operational impact assessment prior to committing to a service level response.
 Any reclassification shall be documented in the work order with a brief rationale.
 The operative severity,
 as confirmed or reclassified by IT staff,
 governs all service level commitments defined in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that triage is attempted within one (1) business hour of work order submission.
 Triage is complete when IT staff have assessed the ticket,
 confirmed or reclassified the severity,
 and initiated or queued the appropriate response.
 Where a submitted work order lacks sufficient information to complete triage,
 IT staff shall document the attempt,
 specify the information required,
 and notify the requester that more information is required.
 Service level clocks shall be paused for the duration of pending information status and shall resume upon receipt of the required information from the requester.
 Work orders that remain in pending information status without requester response for five (5) consecutive business days shall be closed by the assigned technician or queue reviewer,
 with closure rationale documented in the work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Service Level Commitments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Service level commitments consist of two sequential obligations:
 a response commitment and a resolution or escalation commitment.
 All timeframes are measured in business hours or business days from the completion of triage unless otherwise specified.
 Business hours are defined as Monday through Friday,
 8:00 AM to 5:00 PM,
 excluding Elko County observed holidays.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that service level commitments are met and shall monitor adherence in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Response and resolution commitments by severity level are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Critical severity
\series default
:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Response within one (1) business hour of triage completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Resolution or formal escalation within one (1) business day of triage completion.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Urgent severity
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Response within two (2) business hours of triage completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Resolution or formal escalation within three (3) business days of triage completion.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
High severity
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Response within four (4) business hours of triage completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Resolution or formal escalation within five (5) business days of triage completion.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Normal severity
\series default
:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Response within one (1) business day of triage completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Resolution or formal escalation within ten (10) business days of triage completion.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Low severity
\series default
:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Response within two (2) business days of triage completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Resolution or formal escalation within twenty (20) business days of triage completion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Where a Low severity ticket carries a specified due date at the time of submission,
 that due date governs resolution in lieu of the default twenty (20) business day window.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Resolution commitments apply in full to IT-Managed assets as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 For IT-Supported assets,
 the resolution commitment represents IT's obligation to initiate vendor escalation within the defined window,
 not to guarantee vendor resolution within that timeframe.
 Vendor resolution timelines for IT-Supported assets are governed by the applicable contract or service agreement.
 For Vendor-Managed assets,
 IT's commitment is limited to referral —
 the Information Operations Department shall route the request to the appropriate vendor contact within the response window defined above,
 and resolution execution shall be handled entirely by the vendor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 After-Hours and Emergency Response
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department maintains an on-call capability for after-hours emergencies.
 Severity level alone does not constitute sufficient basis for after-hours on-call activation.
 A situation qualifies for after-hours on-call response only when a mission-critical system supporting public safety operations,
 law enforcement functions,
 or a time-bound legal or financial obligation is completely non-functional and no reasonable operational workaround exists.
 Low and Normal severity tickets are explicitly excluded from after-hours on-call activation by definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall maintain and annually review the authoritative list of systems qualifying as mission-critical for purposes of after-hours on-call activation in the designated system of record.
 The Assistant IT Director shall maintain after-hours contact procedures and on-call rotation schedules in Redmine.
 These operational details are not enumerated in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Vendor SLA Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Any contract or service agreement governing an IT-Supported or Vendor-Managed asset entered into or renewed following the effective date of this policy shall include defined vendor response and resolution commitments as a condition of the engagement.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that vendor SLA terms are documented at the time of contract execution and recorded in the IT Asset Catalog entry for the applicable system,
 subject to IT Director approval.
 Vendor SLA performance shall be monitored by the Assistant IT Director in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and evaluated under the vendor compliance framework established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Where an existing contract does not include defined service level terms,
 the Assistant IT Director shall identify the gap,
 document it in the IT Asset Catalog,
 and present it to the IT Director no later than ninety (90) days prior to the next available renewal opportunity so that incorporation of vendor SLA terms may be pursued at renewal.
\end_layout

